commit_message:
Fix v3/volumes.py VolumeController super(...) parameters

VolumeController and the __init__ call has the signature:
def __init__(self, ext_mgr):

But the super call incorrectly has:
super(VolumeController, self).__init__(volumes_v2.VolumeController)
this should be:
super(VolumeController, self).__init__(ext_mgr)

Change-Id: I9b0722f3ef5ca59cd9b6ed9a81c19dee120ad95d
Fixes-Bug: 1580278

subject: Generate only one pair of wwpns when instance has multiple block devices
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2016-05-15 03:28:55.000000000', 'files': ['nova_powervm/tests/virt/powervm/volume/test_npiv.py', 'nova_powervm/virt/powervm/volume/npiv.py'], 'message': 'Generate only one pair of wwpns when instance has multiple block devices

During evacuate of instance with multiple block devices the npiv wwpns
method gets called multiple times and ends up generating wwpn pair each
time, but we need only one pair of wwpn for each fabric across all block
devices. The fix checks the fabric state in addition to the task state
to make sure the new wwpn pair is generated only once. Also the fabric
state of migrating should not be set on the instance since we are
regenarating new wwpn pair.

Closes-bug #1575135

Change-Id: I5d3079f8c3d86274028551d94ee59bf6f1617f89
(cherry picked from commit 551247b6afdc88b5d78a275777def6a8ed0951e8)
'}]
commit_message:
Generate only one pair of wwpns when instance has multiple block devices

During evacuate of instance with multiple block devices the npiv wwpns
method gets called multiple times and ends up generating wwpn pair each
time, but we need only one pair of wwpn for each fabric across all block
devices. The fix checks the fabric state in addition to the task state
to make sure the new wwpn pair is generated only once. Also the fabric
state of migrating should not be set on the instance since we are
regenarating new wwpn pair.

Closes-bug #1575135

Change-Id: I5d3079f8c3d86274028551d94ee59bf6f1617f89
(cherry picked from commit 551247b6afdc88b5d78a275777def6a8ed0951e8)

commit_message:
Fix update target tenant RBAC external path

This fixes the logic to allow updates to wildcard RBAC external
policies. It was broken for two reasons: first, it was using the
wrong kwarg, second, it wasn't considering the target tenant when
determining if the policy was required.

This patch fixes both issues and adds an API test exercising the
update path.

Closes-Bug: #1577100
Change-Id: Id7441ab5c3f3667aa1cc48100286a2a9d480e201
(cherry picked from commit 89297919a73c1e7f86c61d08f3f3d15278f5763a)

commit_message:
Switch from puppetlabs/corosync to puppet/corosync

Project URL on both puppetlabs/corosync [1] and puppet/corosync [2]
are pointed to https://github.com/voxpupuli/puppet-corosync, previous
https://github.com/Puppet-Community/puppet-corosync [3]

also, after applying puppet-openstack-integration [4],
and execute `puppet module list` will get a warning message as follow,

  'openstack-openstack_extras' (v8.0.0) requires 'puppetlabs-corosync' (>=0.1.0 <1.0.0)

reference:

[1] https://forge.puppet.com/puppet/corosync
[2] https://forge.puppet.com/puppetlabs/corosync
[3] https://voxpupuli.org/blog/2016/01/01/voxpupuli/
[4] https://github.com/openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/blob/stable/mitaka/Puppetfile#L133-L135

Change-Id: Iacccd581ce6b07f0844b56290cc47b2c0c7383b4
Signed-off-by: guessi <guessi@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Revert removal of upper constraint on python-kafka

The python-kafka library at 1.0.0 is incompatible with prior
releases and introduced a significant number of performance
regressions and bugs. The Monasca project is a heavy user of
the python-kafka library and this change has broken it.
Unfortunately, we cant' move to the latest version of the
library until all the performance issues and bugs have been
resolved and verified.

We would like to revert back to the previous commit which had
upper contraints specified.

Note, we are trying to get all the Monasca libraries into
requirements, but that work hasn't been completed yet.

Change-Id: I78cf1c725afe7fb8942ff20f3d4332fad0ace8fa

api-ref: reorder parameters.yaml

This reorder's parameters.yaml to the correct sort order, and turns
the info message about incorrect ordering into a warning. After this

commit_message:
Disable nova quota for dsvm functional test

Parallel execution of tacker functional test ends up
creating lots of VMs and eventually fails hitting the
default max instance of 10. This fix disables quota for
tacker functional test suite. However gate VMs still has
upper constraint on resources like 8GB max limit. To avoid
tripping the actual gate VM resource limit reduce concurrency
to a lower number (2).

Change-Id: I3fe8c012b85554fa21b5b4b64378d68e3d979cc2
Closes-Bug: #1572420
(cherry picked from commit d9a9892c87f3c246b4f851b3a696129bf82feab4)

commit_message:
Eager load keypairs in instance metadata

In the review for e83842b80b73c451f78a4bb9e7bd5dfcebdefcab it was
pointed out that keypairs should be added to the eager load list for
get_metadata_for_instance_id. Due to a lack of a proper context in a
thread in the ironic driver, this actually totally broke ironic.
The context problem is being fixed elsewhere, but this should be
eager-loaded to minimize DB queries anyway.

Change-Id: I67b4665bdebd45c66983c6a556d20f367fa7fbdf
Closes-Bug: #1580987

subject: Do not clean NVRAM unless destroy is on same host
revisions:
[{'number': 2, 'created': '2016-05-14 17:58:24.000000000', 'files': ['nova_powervm/virt/powervm/driver.py', 'nova_powervm/tests/virt/powervm/test_driver.py'], 'message': "Do not clean NVRAM unless destroy is on same host

When doing a remote rebuild, the source host will likely come back up at
some point and run the cleanup of the evacuated instances.  When this
was occurring, it would clean out the NVRAM and Slot Store information
from Swift (if the operator was using Swift to store such data).

This information should not be wiped out on the source host re-init
because a second remote rebuild operation will need it.

This change updates the logic that identifies when the NVRAM/Slot
information should be deleted.  It adds a check to make sure that the
instance is on either the same host or is set to None.

The existing checks were not enough.  The destroy_disks would get set to
True unless there was shared storage.  Since there may be a rebuild
without shared storage (think boot from Cinder volume), this flag would
get set to true and wipe out the disks.

It also isn't in the KEEP_NVRAM_STATES, because it is not being shelved.
At the same time, extending the KEEP_NVRAM_STATES is a bit of a zero sum
game.  The state is fluid, and there are some states where you may
actually want to destroy the NVRAM, but in other situations in the same
state keep it.

The addition of the host check seems to be most appropriate for this
scenario of multiple remote rebuilds.

Change-Id: I95a824034d657f31285d85ba412a981d6986d14a
Closes-Bug: #1581803
"}]
commit_message:
Do not clean NVRAM unless destroy is on same host

When doing a remote rebuild, the source host will likely come back up at
some point and run the cleanup of the evacuated instances.  When this
was occurring, it would clean out the NVRAM and Slot Store information
from Swift (if the operator was using Swift to store such data).

This information should not be wiped out on the source host re-init
because a second remote rebuild operation will need it.

This change updates the logic that identifies when the NVRAM/Slot
information should be deleted.  It adds a check to make sure that the
instance is on either the same host or is set to None.

The existing checks were not enough.  The destroy_disks would get set to
True unless there was shared storage.  Since there may be a rebuild
without shared storage (think boot from Cinder volume), this flag would
get set to true and wipe out the disks.

It also isn't in the KEEP_NVRAM_STATES, because it is not being shelved.
At the same time, extending the KEEP_NVRAM_STATES is a bit of a zero sum
game.  The state is fluid, and there are some states where you may
actually want to destroy the NVRAM, but in other situations in the same
state keep it.

The addition of the host check seems to be most appropriate for this
scenario of multiple remote rebuilds.

Change-Id: I95a824034d657f31285d85ba412a981d6986d14a
Closes-Bug: #1581803

commit_message:
Changed the nomenclature of credentials command

Removed the "s" of the "credentials command" in the documentation and renaming the file to credential.rst (instead of credentials)
